{"parentUuid":"9b22d0de-d5a8-4672-b28b-618194b7cd05","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"fca4cbec-e864-421f-b37b-f2723067d26a","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a92d246ad60757cc7","slug":"enumerated-humming-quilt","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01G2EJ7iFEyvWFbfhP1xdzS7","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 407\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/407](https://www.erdosproblems.com/407)\n    23→\n    24→Let $w(n)$ count the number of solutions to $n = 2^a + 3^b + 2^c \\cdot 3^d$ with\n    25→$a, b, c, d \\geq 0$ integers. Is it true that $w(n)$ is bounded by some absolute\n    26→constant?\n    27→\n    28→A conjecture originally due to Newman. This was proved by Evertse, Györy,\n    29→Stewart, and Tijdeman [EGST88]. Bajpai and Bennett [BaBe24] showed that\n    30→$w(n) \\leq 4$ for $n \\geq 131082$ and $w(n) \\leq 9$ for all $n$.\n    31→\n    32→[ErGr80] Erdős, P. and Graham, R., *Old and new problems and results in\n    33→combinatorial number theory*. Monographies de L'Enseignement Mathematique (1980).\n    34→\n    35→[EGST88] Evertse, J.-H., Györy, K., Stewart, C. L., and Tijdeman, R.,\n    36→*S-unit equations and their applications*. New advances in transcendence theory\n    37→(Durham, 1986), Cambridge Univ. Press (1988), 110-174.\n    38→\n    39→[BaBe24] Bajpai, P. and Bennett, M. A., *On sums of four smooth numbers*. (2024).\n    40→-/\n    41→\n    42→namespace Erdos407\n    43→\n    44→/--\n    45→Erdős Problem 407 [ErGr80, p.80]:\n    46→\n    47→There exists an absolute constant $C$ such that for every natural number $n$,\n    48→the number of 4-tuples $(a, b, c, d)$ of natural numbers satisfying\n    49→$n = 2^a + 3^b + 2^c \\cdot 3^d$ is at most $C$.\n    50→-/\n    51→@[category research solved, AMS 11]\n    52→theorem erdos_407 : answer(True) ↔\n    53→    ∃ C : ℕ, ∀ (n : ℕ) (S : Finset (ℕ × ℕ × ℕ × ℕ)),\n    54→      (∀ t ∈ S, n = 2 ^ t.1 + 3 ^ t.2.1 + 2 ^ t.2.2.1 * 3 ^ t.2.2.2) →\n    55→      S.card ≤ C := by\n    56→  sorry\n    57→\n    58→end Erdos407\n    59→"}]},"uuid":"6ea7224f-2089-479a-b8e2-6b2b7b6cfddf","timestamp":"2026-03-10T08:43:48.749Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9b22d0de-d5a8-4672-b28b-618194b7cd05"}
